{"title_page": "Melana Chasmata", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox album\n| italic_title   = yes\n| name         = Melana Chasmata\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Triptykon]]\n| cover        = Melana_Chasmata.jpg\n| released     = 14 April 2014 (Europe) <br /> 15 April 2014 (North America)\n| recorded     = November 2013-January 2014\n| venue        = \n| studio       = {{Collapsible list \n | title = Various\n | Woodshed Studio, [[Landshut]], [[Germany]]\n | Triptykon Bunker, [[Z\u00fcrich, Switzerland]]\n | Corinne's Place, Z\u00fcrich, Switzerland\n}}\n| genre          = {{hlist|[[Extreme metal]]}}\n| length       = 66:52<br/>75:16 (Japanese)\n| label        = {{hlist|Prowling Death|[[Century Media Records|Century Media]]}}\n| producer     = {{hlist|Antje Lange {{small|([[Executive producer|exec.]])}}|[[Thomas Gabriel Fischer|Tom Warrior]] {{small|(also [[Executive producer|exec.]])}}|V. Santura|Michael Zech|}}\n| prev_title   = [[Shatter (EP)|Shatter]]\n| prev_year    = 2010\n| year         = 2014\n}}\n\n{{Album ratings\n| MC        = 82/100 [http://www.metacritic.com/music/melana-chasmata/triptykon/ link]\n| rev1      = [[About.com]]\n| Rev1Score = {{Rating|5|5}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20140419090321/http://heavymetal.about.com/od/triptykon/fl/Triptykon-Melana-Chasmata-Review.htm link]\n| rev2      = All About The Rock\n| Rev2Score = {{Rating|9.5|10}} [http://allabouttherock.co.uk/triptykon-melana-chasmata/ link]\n| rev3      = [[Exclaim!]]\n| Rev3Score = {{Rating|8|10}} [http://exclaim.ca/Reviews/Metal/triptykon-melana_chasmata/ link]\n| rev4      = [[Kerrang!|Kerrang]]\n| Rev4Score = {{Rating|5|5}} [http://www.metacritic.com/music/melana-chasmata/triptykon/ link]\n| rev5      = [[MetalSucks]]\n| Rev5Score = {{Rating|5|5}} [http://www.metalsucks.net/2014/03/24/melana-chasmata-triptykon-real/ link]\n| rev6      = [[Pitchfork Media]]\n| Rev6Score = (7.7/10) [http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/19155-triptykon-melana-chasmata/ link]\n| rev7      = [[PopMatters]]\n| Rev7Score = {{Rating|7|10}} [http://www.metacritic.com/music/melana-chasmata/triptykon/ link]\n| rev8      = [[Sputnikmusic]]\n| Rev8Score = {{Rating|4|5|score=4.1/5 stars}} [https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/62045/Triptykon-Melana-Chasmata/ link]}}\n\n'''''Melana Chasmata''''' is the second full-length album by [[Switzerland|Swiss]] [[extreme metal]] band [[Triptykon]], released through Prowling Death Records/[[Century Media Records]] on 14 April 2014 in Europe and on 15 April 2014 in North America. The album was officially announced on 22 October 2013 by the band's frontman, [[Thomas Gabriel Fischer]] (a.k.a. \"Tom Warrior\"), on his official blog.<ref>[http://fischerisdead.blogspot.com.br/2013/10/triptykon-press-release.html Triptykon Press Release, 2013]</ref>\n\nThe title is in [[Greek language|Greek]] (''\u039c\u03b5\u03bb\u03b1\u03bd\u03ac \u03a7\u03ac\u03c3\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1'') and, according to Fischer, it can be roughly translated as \"black, deep depressions/valleys\" \u2014 or, more literally, \"chasms as [black as] ink\".\n\nThe album's artwork was provided by famous [[Surrealism|Surrealist]] painter [[H. R. Giger]]. It is the third time in his career he has collaborated with Thomas Fischer; Giger also provided artwork for Fischer's former band [[Celtic Frost]]'s first full-length, ''[[To Mega Therion (album)|To Mega Therion]]'', in 1985, and to Triptykon's debut ''[[Eparistera Daimones]]'' in 2010. It was Giger's last album cover before his death, just one month after the album's release.\n\nA [[music video]] for the track \"Aurorae\" was released on 7 August 2014. Another video, to \"Tree of Suffocating Souls\", was released on 17 November 2014. Song ''In The Sleep of Death'' is referring to [[Emily Bront\u00eb]] as about a lost love.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2014/05/emily-bronte-death-metal-darling.html|title=Emily Bront\u00eb: Death Metal Darling|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Paste Magazine|access-date=2016-09-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.triptykon.net/triptykon/Biography.html|title=Triptykon Biography|website=www.triptykon.net|access-date=2016-09-05}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nThe album's official track listing was unveiled by Tom Warrior on his official blog on 7 February 2014.<ref>[http://fischerisdead.blogspot.com.br/2014/02/triptykon-press-release.html Triptykon Press Release, 2014]</ref> [[Breathing (Triptykon song)|A teaser]] [[Single (music)|7\" single]] containing the tracks \"Breathing\" and \"Boleskine House\" was released on 17 March 2014.\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = \n| all_lyrics = Tom Gabriel Warrior\n| all_music = Norman Lonhard, V. Santura, Vanja Slajh, Tom Gabriel Warrior, except where noted\n| title1 = Tree of Suffocating Souls\n| length1 = 7:56\n| title2 = Boleskine House\n| length2 = 7:12\n| title3 = Altar of Deceit\n| length3 = 7:32\n| title4 = [[Breathing (Triptykon song)|Breathing]]\n| length4 = 5:50\n| title5 = Aurorae\n| length5 = 6:17\n| title6 = Demon Pact\n| length6 = 6:07\n| title7 = In the Sleep of Death\n| length7 = 8:10\n| music7 = V. Santura\n| title8 = Black Snow\n| length8 = 12:25\n| title9 = Waiting\n| length9 = 5:55<!--| total_length   = 65:32-->\n| title10 = \n| length10 = \n| title11 = \n| length11 = \n| title12 = \n| length12 = \n| title13 = \n| length13 = \n| title14 = \n| length14 = \n| title15 = \n| length15 = \n| title16 = \n| length16 = \n| title17 = \n| length17 = \n| title18 = \n| length18 = \n| title19 = \n| length19 = \n| title20 = \n| length20 = \n| total_length = 67:23\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| collapsed = no\n| headline  = Japanese bonus track\n| title5  = Into Despair\n| length5 = 7:57\n}}\n\n==Reception==\n''Melana Chasmata'' was met with universal acclaim by both critics and band fans. Writing for All About The Rock, Rich Dodgin said: \"The music of ''Melana Chasmata'' combines heaviness and gothic sensibility to create a fantastically nightmarish soundscape, and if you're a fan of dark ambient music you will love this\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allabouttherock.co.uk/triptykon-melana-chasmata/|publisher=All About The Rock|accessdate=April 13, 2014|author=Rich Dodgin|title=Triptykon - Melana Chasmata -}}</ref> [[MetalSucks]] also praised the album, giving it five stars out of five.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalsucks.net/2014/03/24/melana-chasmata-triptykon-real/|publisher=[[MetalSucks]]|accessdate=April 13, 2014|author=Emperor Rhombus|title=''Melana Chasmata'': Only Triptykon is real}}</ref> It also scored a perfect five out of five on MetalUnderground.com, whose reviewer, Oliver Hynes, stated that \"''Melana Chasmata'' is more than just a metal album... It's art\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalunderground.com/reviews/details.cfm?releaseid=12080|publisher=MetalUnderground.com|accessdate=April 13, 2014|author=Oliver Hynes|title=Triptykon - \"Melana Chasmata\" CD Review}}</ref> ''[[Exclaim!]]'' was also positive about the album and rated it an 8 out of 10, calling it \"an impressive continuation of Tom G. Warrior's often-mighty lineage, addressing each and every one of his strengths while offering something new for those unaware of the history embedded in every note\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/Reviews/Metal/triptykon-melana_chasmata/|publisher=Exclaim!|accessdate=April 20, 2014|author=Sarah Kitteringham|title=Triptykon - Melana Chasmata}}</ref> [[Pitchfork Media]] were slightly less impressed with the album and gave it a 7.7 out of 10, with reviewer Andy O'Connor stating: \"''Melana Chasmata'' is the follow-up [to ''[[Eparistera Daimones]]''], and while it retains much of the strength of its predecessor, it doesn't quite feel like the triumph Triptykon's debut did\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/19155-triptykon-melana-chasmata/|publisher=[[Pitchfork Media]]|accessdate=April 13, 2014|author=Andy O'Connor|title=Triptykon - \"Melana Chasmata\" Album Review}}</ref> ''Melana Chasmata'' was placed as number two on Rolling Stone's 20 Best Metal Albums of 2014. It was voted as \"Album of the Year 2014\" by the editorial staff of Dutch webzine [[Lords of Metal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lordsofmetal.nl/en/specials/view/id/637|publisher=[[Lords of Metal]]|accessdate=January 1, 2015|author=Evil Dr. Smith|title=The Lords Of Metal Top 30 - 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nThe album debuted at No. 171 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and at No. 11 in the Hard Rock Albums chart, with 2,950 copies sold in its debut week in the U.S.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metalinsider.net/columns/metal-by-numbers/metal-by-numbers-423-charts-get-sevendust-ed |title=Metal By Numbers 4/23: Charts get Sevendust-ed |author= Matt Brown |date= April 23, 2014 |work=Metal Insider }}</ref>\n\n==Charts==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Chart (2012)\n! Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{albumchart|BillboardIndependent|33|artist=Triptykon}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Billboard200|171|artist=Triptykon}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|BillboardHardRock|11|artist=Triptykon}}\n|}\n\n==Personnel==\n\n* [[Thomas Gabriel Fischer]] \u2014 guitar, vocals\n* V. Santura \u2014 guitar, vocals\n* Norman Lonhard \u2014 drums, percussion\n* Vanja \u0160lajh \u2014 bass, backing vocals\n\n; Additional musicians\n* Simone Vollenweider \u2014 additional vocals (track 2 & 9)\n* Michael Zech - guitar (track 6)\n* A. Acanthus Gristle - additional vocals (track 8)\n\n; Miscellaneous staff\n* Thomas Gabriel Fischer, V. Santura \u2014 production\n* V. Santura \u2014 mastering\n* [[H. R. Giger]] \u2014 cover art \"Mordor VII\"\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.triptykon.net/ Triptykon's official website]\n* [http://fischerisdead.blogspot.com.br/ Tom Fischer's official blog]\n\n{{Triptykon}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Melana Chasmata}}\n[[Category:2014 albums]]\n[[Category:Triptykon albums]]\n[[Category:Century Media Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums with cover art by H. R. Giger]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox album\n| italic_title   = yes\n| name         = Melana Chasmata\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Triptykon]]\n| cover        = Melana_Chasmata.jpg\n| released     = 14 April 2014 (Europe) <br /> 15 April 2014 (North America)\n| recorded     = November 2013-January 2014\n| venue        = \n| studio       = {{Collapsible list \n | title = Various\n | Woodshed Studio, [[Landshut]], [[Germany]]\n | Triptykon Bunker, [[Z\u00fcrich, Switzerland]]\n | Corinne's Place, Z\u00fcrich, Switzerland\n}}\n| genre          = {{hlist|[[Extreme metal]]}}\n| length       = 66:52<br/>75:16 (Japanese)\n| label        = {{hlist|Prowling Death Records|[[Century Media Records]]}}\n| producer     = {{hlist|Antje Lange {{small|([[Executive producer|exec.]])}}|[[Thomas Gabriel Fischer|Tom Warrior]] {{small|(also [[Executive producer|exec.]])}}|V. Santura|Michael Zech|}}\n| prev_title   = [[Shatter (EP)|Shatter]]\n| prev_year    = 2010\n| year         = 2014\n}}\n\n{{Album ratings\n| MC        = 82/100 [http://www.metacritic.com/music/melana-chasmata/triptykon/ link]\n| rev1      = [[About.com]]\n| Rev1Score = {{Rating|5|5}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20140419090321/http://heavymetal.about.com/od/triptykon/fl/Triptykon-Melana-Chasmata-Review.htm link]\n| rev2      = All About The Rock\n| Rev2Score = {{Rating|9.5|10}} [http://allabouttherock.co.uk/triptykon-melana-chasmata/ link]\n| rev3      = [[Exclaim!]]\n| Rev3Score = {{Rating|8|10}} [http://exclaim.ca/Reviews/Metal/triptykon-melana_chasmata/ link]\n| rev4      = [[Kerrang!|Kerrang]]\n| Rev4Score = {{Rating|5|5}} [http://www.metacritic.com/music/melana-chasmata/triptykon/ link]\n| rev5      = [[MetalSucks]]\n| Rev5Score = {{Rating|5|5}} [http://www.metalsucks.net/2014/03/24/melana-chasmata-triptykon-real/ link]\n| rev6      = [[Pitchfork Media]]\n| Rev6Score = (7.7/10) [http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/19155-triptykon-melana-chasmata/ link]\n| rev7      = [[PopMatters]]\n| Rev7Score = {{Rating|7|10}} [http://www.metacritic.com/music/melana-chasmata/triptykon/ link]\n| rev8      = [[Sputnikmusic]]\n| Rev8Score = {{Rating|4|5|score=4.1/5 stars}} [https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/62045/Triptykon-Melana-Chasmata/ link]}}\n\n'''''Melana Chasmata''''' is the second full-length album by [[Switzerland|Swiss]] [[extreme metal]] band [[Triptykon]], released through Prowling Death Records/[[Century Media Records]] on 14 April 2014 in Europe and on 15 April 2014 in North America. The album was officially announced on 22 October 2013 by the band's frontman, [[Thomas Gabriel Fischer]] (a.k.a. \"Tom Warrior\"), on his official blog.<ref>[http://fischerisdead.blogspot.com.br/2013/10/triptykon-press-release.html Triptykon Press Release, 2013]</ref>\n\nThe title is in [[Greek language|Greek]] (''\u039c\u03b5\u03bb\u03b1\u03bd\u03ac \u03a7\u03ac\u03c3\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1'') and, according to Fischer, it can be roughly translated as \"black, deep depressions/valleys\" \u2014 or, more literally, \"chasms as [black as] ink\".\n\nThe album's artwork was provided by famous [[Surrealism|Surrealist]] painter [[H. R. Giger]]. It is the third time in his career he has collaborated with Thomas Fischer; Giger also provided artwork for Fischer's former band [[Celtic Frost]]'s first full-length, ''[[To Mega Therion (album)|To Mega Therion]]'', in 1985, and to Triptykon's debut ''[[Eparistera Daimones]]'' in 2010. It was Giger's last album cover before his death, just one month after the album's release.\n\nA [[music video]] for the track \"Aurorae\" was released on 7 August 2014. Another video, to \"Tree of Suffocating Souls\", was released on 17 November 2014. Song ''In The Sleep of Death'' is referring to [[Emily Bront\u00eb]] as about a lost love.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2014/05/emily-bronte-death-metal-darling.html|title=Emily Bront\u00eb: Death Metal Darling|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Paste Magazine|access-date=2016-09-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.triptykon.net/triptykon/Biography.html|title=Triptykon Biography|website=www.triptykon.net|access-date=2016-09-05}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nThe album's official track listing was unveiled by Tom Warrior on his official blog on 7 February 2014.<ref>[http://fischerisdead.blogspot.com.br/2014/02/triptykon-press-release.html Triptykon Press Release, 2014]</ref> [[Breathing (Triptykon song)|A teaser]] [[Single (music)|7\" single]] containing the tracks \"Breathing\" and \"Boleskine House\" was released on 17 March 2014.\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = \n| all_lyrics = Tom Gabriel Warrior\n| all_music = Norman Lonhard, V. Santura, Vanja Slajh, Tom Gabriel Warrior, except where noted\n| title1 = Tree of Suffocating Souls\n| length1 = 7:56\n| title2 = Boleskine House\n| length2 = 7:12\n| title3 = Altar of Deceit\n| length3 = 7:32\n| title4 = [[Breathing (Triptykon song)|Breathing]]\n| length4 = 5:50\n| title5 = Aurorae\n| length5 = 6:17\n| title6 = Demon Pact\n| length6 = 6:07\n| title7 = In the Sleep of Death\n| length7 = 8:10\n| music7 = V. Santura\n| title8 = Black Snow\n| length8 = 12:25\n| title9 = Waiting\n| length9 = 5:55<!--| total_length   = 65:32-->\n| title10 = \n| length10 = \n| title11 = \n| length11 = \n| title12 = \n| length12 = \n| title13 = \n| length13 = \n| title14 = \n| length14 = \n| title15 = \n| length15 = \n| title16 = \n| length16 = \n| title17 = \n| length17 = \n| title18 = \n| length18 = \n| title19 = \n| length19 = \n| title20 = \n| length20 = \n| total_length = 67:23\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| collapsed = no\n| headline  = Japanese bonus track\n| title5  = Into Despair\n| length5 = 7:57\n}}\n\n==Reception==\n''Melana Chasmata'' was met with universal acclaim by both critics and band fans. Writing for All About The Rock, Rich Dodgin said: \"The music of ''Melana Chasmata'' combines heaviness and gothic sensibility to create a fantastically nightmarish soundscape, and if you're a fan of dark ambient music you will love this\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allabouttherock.co.uk/triptykon-melana-chasmata/|publisher=All About The Rock|accessdate=April 13, 2014|author=Rich Dodgin|title=Triptykon - Melana Chasmata -}}</ref> [[MetalSucks]] also praised the album, giving it five stars out of five.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalsucks.net/2014/03/24/melana-chasmata-triptykon-real/|publisher=[[MetalSucks]]|accessdate=April 13, 2014|author=Emperor Rhombus|title=''Melana Chasmata'': Only Triptykon is real}}</ref> It also scored a perfect five out of five on MetalUnderground.com, whose reviewer, Oliver Hynes, stated that \"''Melana Chasmata'' is more than just a metal album... It's art\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalunderground.com/reviews/details.cfm?releaseid=12080|publisher=MetalUnderground.com|accessdate=April 13, 2014|author=Oliver Hynes|title=Triptykon - \"Melana Chasmata\" CD Review}}</ref> ''[[Exclaim!]]'' was also positive about the album and rated it an 8 out of 10, calling it \"an impressive continuation of Tom G. Warrior's often-mighty lineage, addressing each and every one of his strengths while offering something new for those unaware of the history embedded in every note\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/Reviews/Metal/triptykon-melana_chasmata/|publisher=Exclaim!|accessdate=April 20, 2014|author=Sarah Kitteringham|title=Triptykon - Melana Chasmata}}</ref> [[Pitchfork Media]] were slightly less impressed with the album and gave it a 7.7 out of 10, with reviewer Andy O'Connor stating: \"''Melana Chasmata'' is the follow-up [to ''[[Eparistera Daimones]]''], and while it retains much of the strength of its predecessor, it doesn't quite feel like the triumph Triptykon's debut did\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/19155-triptykon-melana-chasmata/|publisher=[[Pitchfork Media]]|accessdate=April 13, 2014|author=Andy O'Connor|title=Triptykon - \"Melana Chasmata\" Album Review}}</ref> ''Melana Chasmata'' was placed as number two on Rolling Stone's 20 Best Metal Albums of 2014. It was voted as \"Album of the Year 2014\" by the editorial staff of Dutch webzine [[Lords of Metal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lordsofmetal.nl/en/specials/view/id/637|publisher=[[Lords of Metal]]|accessdate=January 1, 2015|author=Evil Dr. Smith|title=The Lords Of Metal Top 30 - 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nThe album debuted at No. 171 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and at No. 11 in the Hard Rock Albums chart, with 2,950 copies sold in its debut week in the U.S.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metalinsider.net/columns/metal-by-numbers/metal-by-numbers-423-charts-get-sevendust-ed |title=Metal By Numbers 4/23: Charts get Sevendust-ed |author= Matt Brown |date= April 23, 2014 |work=Metal Insider }}</ref>\n\n==Charts==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Chart (2012)\n! Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{albumchart|BillboardIndependent|33|artist=Triptykon}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Billboard200|171|artist=Triptykon}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|BillboardHardRock|11|artist=Triptykon}}\n|}\n\n==Personnel==\n\n* [[Thomas Gabriel Fischer]] \u2014 guitar, vocals\n* V. Santura \u2014 guitar, vocals\n* Norman Lonhard \u2014 drums, percussion\n* Vanja \u0160lajh \u2014 bass, backing vocals\n\n; Additional musicians\n* Simone Vollenweider \u2014 additional vocals (track 2 & 9)\n* Michael Zech - guitar (track 6)\n* A. Acanthus Gristle - additional vocals (track 8)\n\n; Miscellaneous staff\n* Thomas Gabriel Fischer, V. Santura \u2014 production\n* V. Santura \u2014 mastering\n* [[H. R. Giger]] \u2014 cover art \"Mordor VII\"\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.triptykon.net/ Triptykon's official website]\n* [http://fischerisdead.blogspot.com.br/ Tom Fischer's official blog]\n\n{{Triptykon}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Melana Chasmata}}\n[[Category:2014 albums]]\n[[Category:Triptykon albums]]\n[[Category:Century Media Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums with c